<paragraph blockId="12.[684,1213,996,1738]" lastBlockId="13.[108,637,225,388]" lastPageId="13" lastPageNumber="13" pageId="12" pageNumber="12">
REMARKS: The wing tips of 
<specimenCount box="[1021,1117,1645,1669]" pageId="12" pageNumber="12" type="male">one male</specimenCount>
(MUSM 39146) and entire pinnae of 
<specimenCount box="[997,1116,1679,1703]" pageId="12" pageNumber="12" type="female">one female</specimenCount>
(FMNH 203358) specimen were white. Twenty-one indi- viduals were captured and released, 
<quantity box="[540,588,225,249]" metricMagnitude="-1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.286" pageId="13" pageNumber="13" unit="in" value="9.0">9 in</quantity>
the Waqanki and 
<quantity box="[260,314,260,284]" metricMagnitude="-1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.048" pageId="13" pageNumber="13" unit="in" value="12.0">12 in</quantity>
El Diamante localities. Of the released individuals, 
<specimenCount box="[340,470,295,319]" pageId="13" pageNumber="13" type="female">two females</specimenCount>
were pregnant (El Diamante) and two others were lactating (one from each locality).
</paragraph>
